Diagnosis. Male distinguished by palp appearing a bit skew; by configuration of palp, notably shape of tegular apophysis, with two well separated pointed protrusions in proximal half (Fig. 33), as well as by oblique orientation of hairs on cymbium (Fig. 37; character shared with 
tenasserimensis
); female distinguished by shape of epigyne (e. g., Figs 35 & 40), including corrugation of epigynal cavity bottom as seen from inside (dorsal view: Fig. 41), and long spermathecal stalks (Fig.30).
